summary: "Disconnected tools cost professional services firms billable hours. Measure the cost and integrate."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Professional Services"
author: "Redevise"
---

Your consultants bill 30 hours a week. They spend 8 hours on operations. The operations are not billable. The tools are the problem.

Professional services firms run on disconnected tools. The time tracking does not connect to the project management. The project management does not connect to the CRM. The data moves manually. The manual movement is not billable.

Here is what the cost looks like.

Time entry. Consultants enter time into a system. The system does not connect to the project. Someone manually reconciles. 2 hours a week per consultant.

Status updates. Consultants update project status. The status does not flow to the client portal. Someone manually updates. 1 hour a week per consultant.

Resource allocation. Managers allocate resources. The allocation does not connect to the time tracking. Someone manually coordinates. 3 hours a week per manager.

Total per consultant: 6 hours a week. 312 hours a year. At a billing rate of $200 an hour, that is $62,400 per year in lost billable time.

I integrated tools for a professional services firm in 2024. The firm had 25 consultants. The estimated recovered billable time was 15 hours a week. The annual value was $150,000. The integration cost was $28,000.

The teams that accept disconnection are the ones losing billable hours. The teams that integrate are the ones reclaiming them.

Measure the disconnection time. Integrate the tools. Reclaim the hours.
